  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in the shop. When young folks come in, especially those from backgrounds where they've been told they don't belong in tech or engineering, their hands shake before even touching a wrench. I remember a kid once telling me he couldn't fix a car because 'he wasn't smart enough.' That's stereotype threat in a nutshell: the fear of confirming a negative stereotype about oneself. It's not about intelligence; it's about the psychological weight of being labeled 'not one of us.' As a mechanic who's worked with generations of hands-on learners, I've noticed that when people feel they don't fit the mold, they shut down before they even start. Addressing it means creating spaces where people can learn without the fear of judgment. We need mentors who understand these dynamics, not just lectures. In my shop, we have a 'no judgment' policy for trying new things—whether it's using a new tool or asking a question. That kind of support helps people feel safe enough to engage. But it's not just about the shop; it's about how society frames who can succeed in STEM. I've seen it in my own community, where some families avoid science because they think it's 'for boys.' We need to challenge those beliefs early, not just in schools but in everyday conversations. As someone who's spent decades fixing things, I know that the best tools aren't just in the hands of the skilled—they're in the minds of those who feel they belong. If we can help people see themselves as capable, not limited by stereotypes, then STEM will be a place where everyone can thrive, not just those who've been told they don't belong.",
